And so, as Patroclus, Menoetius\'92 fine son, looked after\uc0\u8232 wounded Eurypylus in his hut, Trojans and Achaeans\u8232 kept fighting on in clusters. The Danaan ditch\u8232 and the high broad wall weren\'92t going to hold out long.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\u8232 They\'92d built the wall, then dug the ditch around it,\u8232 to protect the ships and guard the ample plunder\u8232 stored inside. But they\'92d built it without sanction\u8232 from immortal gods\'97they\'92d made no splendid offering,\u8232 no sacrifices to the gods, asking them to keep\u8232 their swift ships safe, so the wall soon fell apart.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a010\u8232 As long as Hector lived and Achilles\'92 anger\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[10]\u8232 did not relent and Priam\'92s city wasn\'92t captured,\u8232 the huge Achaean wall remained intact.\u8232 But after so many of the finest Trojans died,\u8232 many Achaeans, too, though many did survive,\u8232 in the war\'92s tenth year, Priam\'92s city was destroyed.\u8232 When Achaeans sailed back to their dear native land,\u8232 then Poseidon and Apollo planned to erase that wall,\u8232 by stirring up the raging power of all rivers\u8232 flowing from Mount Ida to the sea\'97Rhesus,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a020\u8232 Heptaporus, Caresus, Rhodius, Granicus,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[20]\u8232 Aesepus, the sacred Scamander and Simoeis,\u8232 where many ox-hide shields and helmets had fallen\u8232 in the dust, along with a race of people half-divine.\u8232 Phoebus Apollo merged the mouths of all these rivers,\u8232 then for nine days drove the flood against the rampart.\u8232 Zeus brought constant rain to wash the wall away\u8232 into the sea more quickly. And Poseidon, too,\u8232 the Earthshaker himself, holding his trident,\u8232 led the work, his waves eroding all foundations,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a030\u8232 wood and stone Achaeans had worked so hard to set there.\u8232 He smoothed the shores of the fast-flowing Hellespont,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[30]\u8232 covering huge beaches once again with sand. The wall gone,\u8232 he changed the rivers, so they flowed on as before,\u8232 their lovely waters in their customary channels.\u8232 All this Apollo and Poseidon would do later on.\
But then the din of war raged round the sturdy wall.\uc0\u8232 The battered timbers on the tower rattled.\u8232 Argives, broken by Zeus\'92 whip, were all hemmed in\u8232 beside their hollow ships, held back by fear of Hector,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a040\u8232 whose powerful presence scared them, for, as before,\u8232 he battled like a whirlwind. Just as some wild boar\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[40]\u8232 or lion faced with dogs and huntsmen keeps turning,\u8232 confident of his strength, and men form in a line,\u8232 preparing to go against the beast, hurling spears\u8232 in volleys from their hands\'97still it doesn\'92t tremble,\u8232 show any fear in its brave heart, but its courage\u8232 kills the beast\'97repeatedly it whirls itself around,\u8232 threatening the ranks of men\'97that\'92s how Hector then\u8232 moved through the troops, urging men to attack the ditch\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a050\u8232 and charge across it. But his swift-footed horses balked,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[50]\u8232 standing at the very edge, neighing loudly,\u8232 terrified because the trench was wide to cross.\u8232 They couldn\'92t easily jump over it or get through.\u8232 On both sides there were steep banks along its length,\u8232 with many large sharp stakes driven in the upper edge,\u8232 set there by Achaea\'92s sons as a protection\u8232 against their enemies. There was no easy way\u8232 horses pulling chariots with wheels could move across.\u8232 Even men on foot weren\'92t confident about it.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a060\u8232 Then Polydamas, coming up beside bold Hector, said:\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[60]\
\'93Hector, you other leaders, you allies,\uc0\u8232 it\'92s foolish to think of driving our swift horses\u8232 through this trench. It\'92s difficult to get across,\u8232 with those sharpened stakes projecting from it,\u8232 right by the Achaean wall. There\'92s no way\u8232 any charioteer could get down and fight.\u8232 There\'92s not much room. I think we\'92d get badly hurt.\u8232 If high-thundering Zeus intends to help the Trojans\u8232 and harm Achaeans, wipe them out completely,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a070\u8232 I\'92d prefer that happened right away,\u8232 so Achaeans all die here, far from Argos,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[70]\u8232 unremembered. But if they turn us back,\u8232 drive us from the ships, and trap us in the trench,\u8232 and if Achaeans then reorganize,\u8232 I don\'92t think any of us will get back\u8232 to our city with the news. But come,\u8232 let\'92s all agree to what I now propose\'97\u8232 attendants should hold the horses at the ditch.\u8232 We\'92ll arm ourselves with heavy weapons,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a080\u8232 then all follow Hector bunched up tightly.\u8232 Achaeans will not push us back, if it\'92s true\u8232 they\'92re already headed for destruction.\'94\
What Polydamas had just proposed pleased Hector.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[80]\uc0\u8232 With his weapons, he jumped from his chariot to the ground.\u8232 The other Trojans did not hesitate. Seeing him do that,\u8232 they leapt quickly from their chariots and left them there.\u8232 Each man told his charioteer to keep the horses\u8232 in good order by the ditch. The men broke up in groups\u8232 and organized themselves to form five companies,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a090\u8232 with each one following its own leadership.\u8232 Some went with Hector and worthy Polydamas.\u8232 They were the best and most numerous, especially keen\u8232 to breach the wall and fight on at the hollow ships.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[90]\u8232 Cebriones went with them as third commander.\u8232 Paris led the second group, along with Agenor\u8232 and Alcathous. Helenus and godlike De\'efphobus,\u8232 two sons of Priam, led the third contingent,\u8232 with a third commander, warlike Asius,\u8232 son of Hyrtacus, whose huge horses had carried him\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0100\u8232 all the way from Arisbe by the Selle\'efs river.\u8232 The fourth group of warriors was headed by Aeneas,\u8232 Anchises\'92 brave son, with Archelochus\u8232 and Acamas, two sons of Antenor, well skilled\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[100]\u8232 in all the elements of war. The famous allies\u8232 Sarpedon led. He\'92d chosen to command with him\u8232 Glaucus and warlike Asteropaeus, for they seemed\u8232 clearly the best of all the others, after himself,\u8232 for among them all he was pre-eminent.\u8232 These men linked themselves with sturdy bull\'92s hide shields,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0110\u8232 then in their eagerness made straight for the Danaans.\u8232 They thought no one could stop them, as they charged the ships.\
Other Trojans and their famous allies followed\uc0\u8232 what excellent Polydamas had said to them,\u8232 but Asius, son of Hyrtacus, leader of men,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[110]\u8232 did not want to leave his horses or their driver,\u8232 the attendant charioteer. He brought them with him\u8232 as he went for the ships. The fool! He would not escape\u8232 his grim fate and come back from the ships to windy Troy,\u8232 proudly boasting of his chariot and horses.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0120\u8232 Before that happened an unwelcome fate took him\u8232 on the spear of Deucalion\'92s proud son, Idomeneus.\u8232 Asius moved off to the left of the line of ships,\u8232 where Achaeans used to pass with horse and chariot\u8232 when returning from the plain. That\'92s where he drove\u8232 his chariot and team. He found the gates unbarred\'97\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[120]\u8232 men had drawn the long bolt and were holding them ajar,\u8232 just in case they might save one of their companions\u8232 escaping from the battle to the ships. At those gates\u8232 Asius firmly aimed his horses. His men followed,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0130\u8232 shouting loudly. They thought Achaeans could hold out\u8232 no longer, that they\'92d be assaulting the black ships.\u8232 How wrong they were! For at the gates they found two men,\u8232 two of the finest\'97proud-hearted sons of Lapith spearmen.\u8232 One was powerful Polypoetes, son of Peirithous,\u8232 the other Leonteus, a warrior like man-killing Ares.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[130]\u8232 These two made their stand before the lofty gate,\u8232 like two high-topped mountain oak trees which defy\u8232 wind and rain each and every day, anchored there\u8232 by huge extensive roots\'97just like that, these two men,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0140\u8232 trusting the power in their arms, held their position,\u8232 as great Asius approached. They did not run off.\u8232 Holding bull\'92s hide shields up high, with loud shouts,\u8232 Asius\'92 men came straight for the well-built wall,\u8232 behind lord Asius, Iamenus, Orestes,\u8232 Adamas, Asius\'92 son, Tho\'f6n, and Oenomaus.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[140]\
Up to now, the two Lapiths had been urging\uc0\u8232 well-armed Achaeans from inside the rampart\u8232 to defend their ships. But when they noticed Trojans\u8232 charging the wall and Danaans running off and shouting,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0150\u8232 the two men hurried out to fight beyond the gates.\u8232 Like wild mountain boars taking on a confused mob\u8232 of men and dogs attacking them\'97the beasts charge sideways,\u8232 shattering trees around them, ripping out the roots,\u8232 gnashing their teeth noisily, till someone\u8232 hits them with his spear and takes away their lives\'97\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[150]\u8232 that\'92s how the shining bronze sounded on these two,\u8232 as they moved out against the flying weapons.\u8232 But they fought bravely, relying on their strength\u8232 and on those troops standing on the wall above them,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0160\u8232 who kept throwing rocks down from the sturdy tower,\u8232 defending themselves, their huts, their well-built ships.\u8232 Stones fell to earth like snowflakes which some strong wind\u8232 pushing shadowy clouds drives downward in a storm,\u8232 so they strike the fertile earth, that\'92s how thick and fast\u8232 flying weapons rained down then from Trojans and Achaeans.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[160]\u8232 Helmets and bossed shields rang out as they were hit\u8232 with rocks the size of millstones. Then Asius,\u8232 son of Hyrtacus, groaned in vexation, struck his thigh,\u8232 and cried out:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93Father Zeus, how you love to lie!\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0170\uc0\u8232 I didn\'92t think these warrior Achaeans\u8232 could withstand the force of our all-powerful hands.\u8232 But they\'92re like yellow-banded wasps or bees\u8232 who\'92ve made their home by some rough road\u8232 and won\'92t leave their hollow house, but stay there,\u8232 guarding their offspring from the hunting men.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[170]\u8232 That\'92s how these men refuse to yield the gate,\u8232 though there\'92s just two of them, until they kill us\u8232 or are killed themselves.\'94\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\
